 universities? &#10;Colleges and universities pay the College Board for the lists of high-scoring students so they can contact them. Apparently, the Post can't afford it. What other excuse is there? Sloth? Prejudice? Ignorance? &#10;Or is the Post perhaps so biased against religion of any kind that it will twist the &quot;news&quot; accordingly? &#10;Homeschooling parents pay the taxes that support your kids' &quot;free&quot; public education, and pay again for every bit of teaching, ancillary materials, travel (no yellow school buses for us), and extra-curriculars our kids require. If we put on a play, we have to pay for the school auditorium (paid for with our taxes) that your kids use for free. Ditto if we use the pool. And Athletic fields that we pay for are off-limits. &#10;On the other side of the journalistic coin, where are the stories about the thousands of students withing walking distance from the Post who &quot;graduate&quot; from public high schools without being able to read or write at eighth-grade level? Whose math skills are virtually nonexistent? &#10;That's true, but apparently it isn't news.&#10;The Post wants its readers to think that we Virginians who homeschool under the religious exemption are ... what did they call us in the 1980s? &quot;Poor, undereducated, and easily led.&quot; &#10;Yes, the Post was forced to apologize -- then. But its arrogance and bigotry continue, as evidenced in its selective and slanted reporting on just about everything.Including homeschoolng. &#10;Virginia's successful homeschoolers - and we know hundreds -- read a wide array of literature in several languages. Thank God (yes, there is one, Posties) they don't have to read the Post. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1940" language="en" documentId="395" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="chrisinwien" date="7/29/2013 4:57 AM GMT+0200" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://www.washingtonpost.com/local/students-home-schooling-highlights-debate-over-va-religious-exemption-law/2013/07/28/ee2dbb1a-efbc-11e2-bed3-b9b6fe264871_comment.html?commentID=washingtonpost.com/ECHO/item/1375066677-329-197" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="395" notes="" title="Student’s home-schooling highlights debate over Va. religious exemption law"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="84"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="85" end="110"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="111" end="314"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="51" sofa="1" begin="315" end="523"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="55" sofa="1" begin="524" end="629"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="59" sofa="1" begin="630" end="1052"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="63" sofa="1" begin="1053" end="1334"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="67" sofa="1" begin="1335" end="1377"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="71" sofa="1" begin="1378" end="1561"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="75" sofa="1" begin="1562" end="1750"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="79" sofa="1" begin="1751" end="1940"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47 51 55 59 63 67 71 75 79"/></xmi:XMI>